                VerticalTextAlignment="Center"
                HorizontalTextAlignment="Center"
                Text="The title is the key word of your day, it is the first and sometimes only part of your article that shows the potential you will see and think about if your day was grateful or regular.  So it's important to grab your attention for the next day.

1) Brainstorming.
When you brainstorm a title, you're doing more than that. You're developing a realistic idea about how you spent your day, and you brainstorm with a quick flashback of your day with what you have learned and did to give a name. Let me be clear. The goal of this process is to come up with a truly great idea. That may sound intimidating.

2) Creativity.
It's going to require creativity. It may require using your mind in a way you usually don't. 

3) Information.
The title is, one of the most important parts of a paper. The title is not only printed first (or very close to the top) in an article; it is the part that will be read by most people. These readers must then decide whether the paper contains information that is relevant or interesting for them. The main requirements of a good title can be formulated briefly and sharply: be precise, simple, and short. The best title is one that gives the most accurate information about the content of the paper with the fewest possible words.

4) Start with what, why, how or when.
Generally, the title should indicate answers to the important basic questions: What? Where? How? So when you read it you can judge your actions on that day. It is the summary result.
Starting your sentence with one of these words creates a persuasive effect on the title. You can use them to ask a question or establish the purpose of your article immediately in an understandable way for the reader.
"/>
                    <Label     
                TextColor="#F2D985"
                BackgroundColor="Transparent"
